title: Africa: Conflicts Without Borders 2009 (raw data)
name: Africa: Conflicts Without Borders 2009 (raw data)
description: Conflicts Without Borders, which visualizes conflict in Africa as sub-national and transnational areas of armed conflict, inter-communal strife, and political violence that occurred in the first seven months of 2009. Areas of conflict were drawn around locations of reported conflict incidents in 2009, as well as around concentrations of internally displaced persons inside affected countries and cross-border rebel bases and refugee camps in neighboring countries

properties.SeverityIn: Violence affected 1 million, including 123,300 IDPs (Mar 2009).  74,000 CAR refugees remain in southern Chad (May 2009).
properties.Background: In early 2009, clashes between government forces and rebels, as well as between Rounga and Goula ethnic groups displaced thousands in the north and across Chadian and Cameroonian borders.  Fighting started in 2006 and MINURCAT deployed in 2007.

properties.SeverityIn: In February 2009, Sudan Armed Forces and Sudansese People's  Liberation Army clashed in Malakal.  Fighting resulted in more than 30 civilian deaths, thousands of displaced civilians, and damages to civiiian property (HRW Jun 2009).
properties.Background: Renewed fighting between the former South Sudan rebel force and northern Misseriya tribal militia broke out around the oil-rich Abyei region in 2008.  In Feb 2009, fighting broke out between rival Southern and Northern militias around Malakal.

properties.SeverityIn: In May - Jun 2009,  armed groups near Bignona conducted at least 20 violent carjackings and lootings (IRIN Jun 2009).

properties.SeverityIn: From Nov 2008 - Feb 2009, religious clashes resulted in hundreds killed and thousands displaced (ICG Dec 2008).
properties.Background: Sporadic riots and violence between Muslim and Christian communities intensified in late 2008 and early 2009 in Plateau, Bauchi, and Kaduna States.

properties.SeverityIn: From Mar - Jun 2009, more than 1,000 died and 26,000 were displaced in clashes over land, water, and cattle (HRW Jun 2009).

properties.SeverityIn: In Uganda's Karamoja region, inter-tribal clashes and fighting with military forces resulted in over 50 killed in May - Jun 2009 (OCHA  Jun 2009).
properties.Background: Karimojong fighters launched livestock raids on neighboring tribes and engaged military forces in May -Jun 2009.  The Sudanese Langes pastoralist group also led cross border raids into Kitgum District, Uganda.

properties.SeverityIn: In southwestern Ethiopia, inter-tribal raids resulted in deaths and livestock rustling (CEWARN  Jun 2009).
properties.Background: Conflict over livestock and water rights between Turkana and Dassenech tribes flared up in Oct 2008 and intensified in May - Jun 2009.  Conflict occurred mostly in Omo River delta of southwestern Ethiopia.

properties.SeverityIn: As many as 300 killed and tens of thousands displaced (BBC Feb 2009).
properties.Background: In February 2009 near the border town of Moyale, Ethiopia, Borana and Gehri pastoralist communites clashed over land and water wells.

properties.SeverityIn: Over 50 people killed in Nyeri and Kirinyaga districts in Apr 2009.  At least nine people killed around Isiolo district in Jun 2009  (KRCS Jun 2009).
properties.Background: Violence erupted between Mungiki sect gangs and community vigilantes in Nyeri and Kirinyaga districts, Central Province in Apr 2009.  Samburu raiders rustled livestock around Isiolo district, Eastern province in Jun 2009.

properties.SeverityIn: In Jun 2009, violence resulted in 20 deaths, hundreds of houses burned, and 7,000 people displaced, some crossing  into Tanzania  (KRCS Jun 2009).
properties.Background: In Jun 2009 in the Kuria East division of Nyanza province, Bairege and Nyabashi clans clashed over cattle rustling and disagreements over the planned location of district headquarters.

properties.SeverityIn: Eleven people killed, over 700 families displaced, and loss of livestock  (IRIN Jul 2009).
properties.Background: In July 2009, clashes broke out between the Hared and Mohamoud Nour clans over ownership of Elberdale farmland in Gabiley region.  Families moved into Adwal and Woqooyi Galbeed regions.

properties.SeverityIn: On Mar. 1-2, General Tagme and Presidnet Vieira were assassinated. On Jun 5, a presidential candidiate, two former ministers, and two others were shot dead (ICG Jun 2009).

properties.SeverityIn: At least 100 civilians died in protests and confrontations with police and security forces (ICG Feb 2009).
properties.Background: Violent protests in Antananarivo from late 2008 to early 2009 culminated in a coup d'etat against President Marc Ravalomanana in Mar 2009.

properties.SeverityIn: At least 17 people injured, three women reportedly raped, and political offices burned in political clashes (ICG Apr 2009).
properties.Background: In Mar 2009, post-election clashes broke out between supporters of ruling All People's Congress (APC) and opposition Sierra Leone People's party (SLPP) in Freetown and southern Gendema.

properties.SeverityIn: Over 700 dead and thousands displaced. (Reuters, Aug 2009)
